  "signature": "ed25519:7b3e1a9c4f2d806e5b3a1c9d7f4e2b0a6c8d3e1f5a7b2c4d9e6f1a3b5c7d8e2f",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA plan documented under 21 CFR Part 820 QMS; version-controlled solver binaries with regression test suite achieving ≥95% pass rate across benchmark suite; all three FEA platforms (FDA in-house, Ansys 2022 R2, DePuy Synthes proprietary) independently verified.",
      "rationale": "All three modeling platforms operate under documented software quality management systems. The FDA in-house code is subject to FDA ORA SQA procedures; Ansys 2022 R2 is covered by vendor-issued validation documentation per ISO 9001; DePuy Synthes proprietary code operates under 21 CFR Part 820 design controls. Regression test suites were executed prior to the study and all critical benchmark cases passed. Achieved level 3 exceeds the required level 2 for a medium model risk application."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification benchmarks must include at minimum: (1) patch test for continuum elements, (2) cantilever beam bending under large displacement, and (3) contact patch test. All benchmarks must converge to analytical solution within 1% relative error at the finest mesh density used in production models.",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed for each platform through standard benchmark problems including patch tests, cantilever beam bending, and Hertzian contact problems. All platforms demonstrated convergence to analytical solutions within acceptable tolerances. The required level of 2 reflects that the model employs well-established linear elastic and contact mechanics formulations without novel numerical methods."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate <5% change in all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) between the production mesh and a mesh with at least 1.5× linear element density. Richardson extrapolation or Grid Convergence Index (GCI) must be reported for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence studies were conducted for each of the three FEA platforms. Element size was refined from a coarse baseline to the production mesh density, with a further refinement step to confirm convergence. GCI values for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement were all below 2%, confirming that discretization error is well controlled. The required level 3 reflects the geometric complexity of the pedicle screw thread geometry and the contact interfaces between screw and rod."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must drop below 1×10⁻⁶ (relative) for all load steps; contact force equilibrium must be verified at each converged increment; energy balance error must remain below 0.1% throughout the analysis.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear solver convergence was monitored throughout each simulation. Force residuals and displacement residuals were tracked at each Newton-Raphson iteration. All simulations achieved full convergence at each load increment with no divergence events. Energy balance errors remained below 0.05% across all runs. The required level 2 is appropriate given the use of well-established implicit solvers for a quasi-static loading scenario."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Use error was mitigated through a structured modeling protocol shared across all three FEA teams prior to model construction. Independent cross-checks were performed: each team reviewed the boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions of at least one other team's model. A pre-analysis checklist based on ASME V&V 40 Table 1 was completed and archived for each platform. The achieved level 3 reflects the multi-team independent review process, which exceeds the minimum required level 2 for this medium-risk application. The required level was set at 2 because the modeling workflow involves experienced analysts following a well-documented protocol, reducing the probability of consequential user error."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form adequacy is confirmed when the normalized validation metric E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs across all three modeling platforms, where E is the mean signed error and uval is the combined experimental and model uncertainty at 95% confidence. Additionally, no systematic bias exceeding 5% shall be present in any single QoI.",
      "rationale": "The model employs linear elastic titanium alloy material properties calibrated from coupon testing, with nonlinear contact interfaces at the screw-rod and screw-vertebral body interfaces. Geometric fidelity was confirmed against CT-derived measurements of the physical constructs. The model form assumptions (small-strain elasticity for the metallic components, rigid vertebral body surrogate) are well-supported by the literature and consistent with the ASTM F1717 test configuration. Required level 3 reflects that contact mechanics and geometric nonlinearity are significant contributors to construct response."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties must be sourced from lot-specific coupon testing or peer-reviewed literature with stated uncertainty bounds. Geometric inputs must be derived from calibrated CMM or CT measurements with dimensional uncertainty reported. Sensitivity analysis must identify the top three input parameters by influence on each QoI, and their combined uncertainty contribution must be quantified.",
      "rationale": "Material properties for Ti-6Al-4V rod and screw components were obtained from lot-specific tensile coupon testing (n=5 per lot) and are consistent with ASTM F136 specifications. Geometric inputs were derived from calibrated coordinate measuring machine (CMM) data. A one-at-a-time sensitivity analysis identified rod diameter, screw shank diameter, and rod-screw interface friction coefficient as the dominant inputs. Combined input uncertainty was propagated using Monte Carlo simulation (N=1000 samples) and contributed less than 3% to QoI variability."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At least N=10 physical constructs tested; constructs sourced from production lots with documented dimensional inspection; inter-specimen variability in key geometric dimensions (rod diameter, screw shank diameter) must be reported and incorporated into model uncertainty quantification.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (n=6 at Lab A, n=5 at Lab B). All constructs were assembled from production-representative components with dimensional inspection records. Inter-specimen variability in rod diameter (CV=0.8%) and screw shank diameter (CV=0.5%) was low and consistent with manufacturing tolerances. The sample size of N=11 provides adequate statistical power to characterize experimental variability for comparison with the model ensemble."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span at least two load levels or two fixture configurations to assess model predictive capability across the operating envelope. Alternatively, a single condition is acceptable only if supported by a documented sensitivity analysis demonstrating that the chosen condition is representative of the worst-case COU scenario.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration (5° offset, standard UHMWPE blocks). While this configuration is the regulatory standard for pedicle screw construct testing, it represents a single test condition. The achieved level 2 reflects this limitation: only one load configuration was evaluated, and no multi-condition sweep was performed. The required level 3 was not met; however, the single condition is the accepted regulatory benchmark and the model's predictive capability at this condition is well-characterized. This shortfall is acknowledged and accepted by the assessment team as consistent with current regulatory practice."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters used in the validation simulation must be traceable to measured or specified values from the physical test specimens; any parameter not directly measurable must have its assumed value justified and a sensitivity analysis performed to bound its influence on QoI predictions.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency matrix was constructed mapping each FEA input to its physical test counterpart. All geometric parameters were matched to CMM measurements from the tested constructs. Material properties were matched to lot-specific coupon data. The UHMWPE block stiffness, which could not be directly measured during the test, was assigned from published literature and a sensitivity study confirmed its influence on stiffness QoI was below 2%. Friction coefficients at the screw-rod interface were estimated from tribological literature and bounded by sensitivity analysis."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison must use the normalized validation metric E/uval at 95% confidence for each QoI. Acceptance threshold: E/uval < 1.96 for all QoIs across all three modeling platforms. Additionally, percent difference between mean predicted and mean experimental values must be reported and must not exceed 10% for any QoI.",
      "rationale": "Output comparison was performed using the ASME V&V 40 normalized validation metric for all three QoIs across all three FEA platforms. E/uval values ranged from 0.31 to 1.44 across the nine QoI-platform combinations, all below the 1.96 threshold. Percent differences between mean predicted and mean experimental values were: stiffness 3.2%, yield force 5.8%, force at 40 mm 4.1%. All comparisons satisfied the pre-established acceptance bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are directly specified in ASTM F1717 and are the regulatory endpoints used to characterize pedicle screw construct mechanical performance. These QoIs are clinically relevant because stiffness governs load transfer to adjacent levels, yield force indicates the onset of permanent deformation, and force at 40 mm bounds catastrophic failure. The FEA model was explicitly designed to predict these endpoints. The required level was set at 2 because the QoIs are standardized and their clinical relevance is well-established in the literature; achieved level 3 reflects the direct traceability of each QoI to both the regulatory standard and clinical failure modes."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must replicate the COU geometry (non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw), loading mode (ASTM F1717 compression-bending), and material system (Ti-6Al-4V) to a degree sufficient to support direct model credibility transfer. Any deviations from COU conditions must be documented and their impact on model credibility quantified.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities were designed to directly replicate the COU: the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw design, the same ASTM F1717 compression-bending protocol, and the same Ti-6Al-4V material system used in the clinical device. Testing was conducted at two independent laboratories to assess inter-laboratory variability. No surrogate geometries or scaled models were employed. The validation scenario is therefore highly relevant to the COU, and no material deviations from COU conditions were introduced during the validation campaign."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-dr-20260419",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The overall credibility assessment is accepted at the Medium assurance level. Twelve of thirteen credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. The single shortfall — Test conditions achieving level 2 against a required level 3 — is acknowledged and accepted on the basis that the ASTM F1717 single-condition protocol is the established regulatory benchmark for pedicle screw construct evaluation, and the model's predictive capability at this condition is thoroughly characterized. All three QoIs satisfy the pre-established quantitative acceptance bounds (E/uval < 1.96; percent difference < 10%) across all three independent FEA platforms. The multi-team, multi-laboratory validation design provides strong evidence of model generalizability within the defined COU.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
